    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the principal balance seems to play hide and seek with your hard-earned money. Imagine, if you will, a mischievous goblin named Interest, who loves to sneak into your monthly payments and take a little bit of your gold. Each month, Interest calculates his share by multiplying the remaining principal balance by the loan's interest rate. This goblin's share is then added to the principal, making it a bit larger. So, instead of your payments going straight to reducing the principal, a portion of it is goblin Interest's feast, and the rest goes towards the principal. It's like giving Interest a little piece of your pie, while the rest goes to the principal. And just like goblins, Interest doesn't like to share, so he keeps taking his share until the loan is fully paid off.",
